tors—social reformers, labor activists, and ordinary laboring people—made use of the available cultural narratives about family, gender, and sexuality to comprehend changes in turn-of-the-century America.In the decades after the Civil War, Philadelphia was an important center of charity, child protection, and labor reform. Drawing on the rich records of the Pennsylvania Society to Protect Children from Cruelty, Broder assesses the intentions and consequences of reform efforts devoted to women and children at the turn of the century. Her research provides an eloquent study of how the terms used by social workers and their clients to discuss the condition of poverty continue to have a profound influence on social policies and develops a complex historical perspective on how social policy and representations of poor families have been and remain mutually influential.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aChild welfarezPennsylvaniazPhiladelphiaxHistoryy19th century. 0aFamily social workzPennsylvaniazPhiladelphiaxHistoryy19th century. 0aPoor familieszPennsylvaniazPhiladelphiaxHistoryy19th century. 0aWorking class familieszPennsylvaniazPhiladelphiaxHistoryy19th century. 4aBooks of Regional Interest. 7aHISTORY / United States / 19th Century.2bisacsh  aAmerican History.  aAmerican Studies.  aBooks of Regional Interest.  aGender Studies.  aHistory.  aWomen's Studies.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn Press eBook Package American Historyz978311041349608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn Press eBook Package Complete Collectionz978311041345808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Pennsylvania Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311045954840uhttps://doi.org/10.9783/978081220145140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780812201451423Cov